The Mycelium Throne~
The tunnel ends in a chamber of absolute, oppressive scale — the ceiling is lost in darkness above, the walls are at the extreme edge of any reasonable light source, and the floor slopes gently down to a central depression where an enormous mass of fused fungal matter has grown into the rough shape of a throne.  The throne is alive: its surface pulses slowly with deep, slow contractions, and from its base, the mycelium network spreads outward in every direction across the floor, the threads thick as rope near the throne and thinning to hair-fineness as they disappear up the walls.  The air has a quality here of being a medium for something that already occupies it, something vast and fungal and patient that has been sitting in this chair of its own flesh for longer than the forest above has existed.  Spore clouds wreathe the throne in lazy orbits, drifting on currents of their own making, and the silence is not empty but full of the enormous, quiet respiration of the organism that rules this chamber.  Nothing else grows here.  Nothing else could.~
