#1069
The Amber Forest Floor~
The same amber fluid that drips through sections of the Fungal Hollows below surfaces here — pooling in shallow depressions of the forest floor and coating the roots of trees where they meet the ground.  The amber has hardened in exposed areas into a glassy surface that catches and distorts light, and the pooled liquid areas are deep enough to submerge a boot.  Preserved in the hardened sections, visible through the amber like specimens in a museum, are several generations of fallen leaves, dead insects, and at one point an entire small creature frozen in mid-motion.  The tree roots coated in amber have swollen around it over time, incorporating the coating into their structure.~
