#1070
The Spongy Ground~
The forest floor here is deeply soft — not the crunch-then-sink of the leaf-carpet sections above but a genuine sponginess, the soil beneath the thin surface layer permeated with water and fungal matter to a depth that swallows boot-heels and resists withdrawal with a gentle sucking.  Progress is slow here, each step requiring effort to extract, and the ground makes quiet, wet sounds with each footfall.  The trees growing from this substrate have compensated with extraordinarily elaborate above-ground root structures, their roots forming buttresses that keep the trunks upright despite the unstable ground beneath.~
